\begin{lemma*}
  {}
  Let~$\tup{\sgrpA, \mtimes}$ be a semigroup. If there exists elements~$1 \in \sgrpA$ and~$1' \in \sgrpA$ such that~$\tup{\sgrpA, \mtimes, 1}$ and $\tup{\sgrpA, \mtimes, 1'}$ are each monoids, then~$1 = 1'$ must hold.
  In other words, the neutral element of a monoid is uniquely determined by the underlying semigroup structure.\end{lemma*}
